"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">74</A>
Consul suffectus in 17 <SPAN CLASS="small">A.D.</SPAN>; proconsul of Africa for three years (27‑30 <SPAN CLASS="small">A.D.</SPAN>?); governor of Syria under Claudius. He appears again in the <I>Annals</I> at
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Annals/2C*.html#79
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,5,WIDTH,140)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<SPAN CLASS="small">II</SPAN>.79</A>;
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Annals/4D*.html#56
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<SPAN CLASS="small">IV</SPAN>.56</A>;
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Annals/6B*.html#47
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<SPAN CLASS="small">VI</SPAN>.47‑8</A>;
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Annals/11A*.html#10
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<SPAN CLASS="small">XI</SPAN>.10</A>; and, since he had literary tastes (<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">vetustis honoribus et inlustris studiis</SPAN>,
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Annals/6B*.html#47
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<SPAN CLASS="small">VI</SPAN>.47</A>), it has been conjectured that some of the details of Germanicus' last days may rest ultimately on his authority.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note75" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Annals/2C*.html#ref75
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">75</A>
Cn. Sentius Saturninus, consul suffectus in 4 <SPAN CLASS="small">A.D.</SPAN> A <A ID="p501x"></A>fragmentary inscription proves that his appointment was recognized as valid by Tiberius.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note76" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Annals/2C*.html#ref76
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">76</A>
Off the Carian coast, in the province of Asia.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note77" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Annals/2C*.html#ref77
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">77</A>
From the Syrian legions: men, presumably, who owed their promotion to Piso (see above,
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Annals/2C*.html#55
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,5,WIDTH,140)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
chap. 55</A>).


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note78" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Annals/2C*.html#ref78
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">78</A>
Since the death of Philopator
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Annals/2B*.html#42
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(chap. 42)
	</A>
there were two of these principalities remaining: Olba, north of Pompeiopolis; and Trachea, the western part of Cilicia, then held by Archelaus of Cappadocia.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note79" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Annals/2C*.html#ref79
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">79</A>
Marsus' citation had no legal force, as it was only when the president of the court had formally received the charge that a day (normally the tenth from the date) was fixed for the appearance of the parties. The true insolence of the answer lies, however, in the tacit assumption that the case had no features so exceptional as to necessitate a change from the usual procedure.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note80" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Annals/2C*.html#ref80
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">80</A>
The modern Ladikîeh (Latakia), nearly opposite the <SPAN CLASS="whole">north-eastern</SPAN> extremity of Cyprus: the other Syrian town of the name lay near Lebanon.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note81" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Annals/2C*.html#ref81
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">81</A>
Now Kilindria (the Turkish <SPAN CLASS="archaic">Tchilindere</SPAN>).


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note82" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Annals/2C*.html#ref82
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">82</A>
The legion in which Piso's influence was strongest (see above,
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Annals/2C*.html#79
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,5,WIDTH,140)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
chap. 79</A>).


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note83" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Annals/2C*.html#ref83
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">83</A>
Drusus was the step-son of Augustus, Germanicus the adopted son of Tiberius.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note84" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Annals/2C*.html#ref84
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">84</A>
For the belief that Drusus designed to restore the republic, see
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Annals/1C*.html#33
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<SPAN CLASS="small">I</SPAN>.33
	</A>
and
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Claudius*.html#1
	"TARGET="Suetonius_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EPlusL,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Suet. <I>Claud.</I> 1</A>. He died in Germany from the consequences of a riding accident (<A HREF="
https://www.livius.org/sources/content/livy/livy-periochae-141-145/#142.1
	"TARGET="Livius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EPlusL2,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">Liv. <I>epit.</I> 142</A>;<A CLASS="correction"
onMouseOver="return Ebox('The printed edition<BR>has '+BadF+'140'+CloseF+'',WIDTH,120)"
onMouseOut="nd();">º</A> <SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">νόσῳ τινί</SPAN>,
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Cassius_Dio/55*.html#1.4
	"TARGET="Cassius_Dio_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Dio,WIDTH,190)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
D. Cass. <SPAN CLASS="small">LV</SPAN>.1</A>): the absurd and inevitable story of his poisoning by order of Augustus is mentioned and rejected by Suetonius, <I>l.c.</I>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note85" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Annals/2C*.html#ref85
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">85</A>
Suetonius is more explicit
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Caligula*.html#6
	"TARGET="Suetonius_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EPlusL,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(<I>Cal.</I> 6)</A>:— <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Passim cum luminibus et victimis in Capitolium concursum est ac paene revolsae templi


<A ID="p511x"></A>fores, ne quid gestientis vota reddere moraretur</SPAN>. He quotes the verse with which they woke Tiberius:— <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Salva Roma, salva patria, salvus est Germanicus.</SPAN>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note86" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Annals/2C*.html#ref86
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">86</A>
In addition to lays in honour of the gods severally, this primitive and unintelligible hymn (<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Saliorum carmina vix sacerdotibus suis satis intellecta</SPAN>,
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Quintilian/Institutio_Oratoria/1B*.html#6.40
	"TARGET="Quintilian_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,1,WIDTH,165)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Quint. <SPAN CLASS="small">I</SPAN>.6.40</A>) contained <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">carmina in universos sermones composita</SPAN>, in which the name of Augustus had already been inserted.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note87" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Annals/2C*.html#ref87
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">87</A>
See
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Annals/1C*.html#54
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<SPAN CLASS="small">I</SPAN>.54</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note88" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Annals/2C*.html#ref88
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">88</A>
In company with the images of the gods.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note89" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Annals/2C*.html#ref89
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">89</A>
Augustalis.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note90" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Annals/2C*.html#ref90
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">90</A>
<SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">Ὁ μὲν γὰρ Ἀμανὸς . . . περικλείει τὸν Ἰσσικὸν κόλπον ἅπαντα</SPAN>
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Strabo/12B*.html#2.2
	"TARGET="Strabo_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Strabo,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Strab<SPAN CLASS="emend">.</SPAN> 535</A>: Nipperdey gives the modern name as Akma Dagh.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note91" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Annals/2C*.html#ref91
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">91</A>
Actually the suburb was Daphne, the city <SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">Ἄντιόχεια ἡ ἐπὶ Δάφνῃ</SPAN>: a rather curious inaccuracy in view of the great celebrity of Daphne (see, for instance, Munro, <I>Aetna</I>, pp40‑43)<!--</A>MUNRO:AETNA-->.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note92" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Annals/2C*.html#ref92
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">92</A>
In the Palatine Library (see above,
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Annals/2B*.html#37
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
chap. 37</A>). The <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">clipeus</SPAN> was a disk, usually of bronze, with the portrait engraved on it: Pliny actually derives the word from <SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">γλύφω</SPAN>
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Pliny_the_Elder/35*.html#3
	"TARGET="Pliny"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Pliny,WIDTH,205)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(<I>H. N.</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">XXXV</SPAN>.3)</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note93" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Annals/2C*.html#ref93
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">93</A>
The date of the annual <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">travectio</SPAN>, or review of the <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">equites Romani equo publico</SPAN>; long obsolete, but revived by Augustus
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#38
	"TARGET="Suetonius_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EPlusL,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(Suet. <I>Aug.</I> 38)</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note94" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Annals/2C*.html#ref94
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">94</A>
Pliny
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Pliny_the_Elder/35*.html#20
	"TARGET="Pliny"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Pliny,WIDTH,205)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(<I>H. N.</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">XXXV</SPAN>.4)
	</A>
describes him as recently dead at an advanced age; as having held the proconsulate of Gallia


<A ID="p515x"></A>Narbonensis; and as being an enthusiastic amateur of painting — <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">sed ea res inrisu et contumeliae erat</SPAN>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note95" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Annals/2C*.html#ref95
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">95</A>
A proverbially insignificant and barren island (now <SPAN CLASS="source">Serpho</SPAN>[<SPAN CLASS="source">s</SPAN>] in the Cyclades between Cythnus and Siphnus.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note96" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Annals/2C*.html#ref96
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">96</A>
The scandals which roused Tiberius to action may be read in
	<A HREF="
https://penelope.uchicago.edu/josephus/ant-18.html#S3.4
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,2,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Jos. <I>A. J.</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">XVIII</SPAN>.3.4‑5</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note97" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Annals/2C*.html#ref97
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">97</A>
The eligible age was from six to ten years, the vows being obligatory for thirty.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note98" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Annals/2C*.html#ref98
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">98</A>
"Though a large, not an unusual dowry," Mayor on Juv. <SPAN CLASS="small">X</SPAN>.335<!-- DON'T LINK, except to Mayor -->. He quotes, <I>inter alia</I>,
	<A HREF="
http://www.thelatinlibrary.com/sen/sen.consolatione3.shtml
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(EClickHere+'Seneca\'s<BR>Consolatio ad Helviam'+Lat2+LatSearch+'deciens</SPAN>',WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Sen. <I>Cons. ad Helv.</I> 12.6</A>, <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">pantomimae deciens sestertio nubunt</SPAN>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note99" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Annals/2C*.html#ref99
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">99</A>
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Annals/1E*.html#72
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<SPAN CLASS="small">I</SPAN>.72</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note100" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Annals/2C*.html#ref100
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">100</A>
By his own definition
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Cassius_Dio/57*.html#8.2
	"TARGET="Cassius_Dio_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Dio,WIDTH,190)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(D. Cass. <SPAN CLASS="small">LVII</SPAN>.8)</A>, to his slaves he was "<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">dominus</SPAN>"; to his soldiers, "<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">imperator</SPAN>"; to the rest of the world, "<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">princeps</SPAN>." For his occupations he preferred <!-- Loeb has a comma plus a single quotemark here, at the beginning of the line, instead of a double quotemark --><SPAN CLASS="emend">"</SPAN>laborious" rather than "sacred" as an adjective
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Tiberius*.html#27
	"TARGET="Suetonius_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EPlusL,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(Suet. <I>Tib.</I> 27)</A>. Diocletian introduced the "dominate."


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note101" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Annals/2C*.html#ref101
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">101</A>
Since his power must be reckoned from the defeat of Varus, his death would fall in 21 <SPAN CLASS="small">A.D.</SPAN>



	<HR CLASS="endnotes"><A ID="endnotes_T"></A>
	<H2>
Thayer's Note:
	</H2>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note:Appuleia_Varilla" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Annals/2C*.html#ref:Appuleia_Varilla
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,170)"
onMouseOut="nd();">a</A>
At least one reader of this passage has been more attentive than yours truly in transcribing it, and indeed than the Loeb editor/translator himself: Julius Koch, to whom thanks, writes me that

<DIV CLASS="prose">
	<P>
in Tac. <I>Ann.</I> 2.50.1 Appuleia Varilla is translated as "the niece of Augustus' sister" when she is in fact her granddaughter. The error stems from the Loeb edition and as the Latin is "<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">neptem</SPAN>" both terms would work; however, since the Loeb translation was published it has become clear that she was the granddaughter of Octavia Major — or at least Ursula <SPAN CLASS="whole">Vogel-Widemann</SPAN> (1965, 450) is quite certain that she is the woman mentioned in AE 1966, 422 as the daughter of S. Appuleius; and Ronald Syme (1989, 317) follows her reasoning.
	<P>
<SPAN CLASS="outquote">[. . .]</SPAN> "niece of his sister" is a little odd to begin with as any niece of Augustus' sister would of course also be his niece.
</DIV>



